			<ns0:name>b...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/105821748722532785568/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">just to belabor the obvious: jmp_buf containing data structures are inherently non-portable across CPU architectures -- there should be no hope that programmers should be able to write such data structures to persistent storage and switch to another CPU architecture (or send such a data object to a machine w/ a different CPU architecture) and expect things to work.

does the requirement to have consistent sizes actually make sense here?!?</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2010-11-22T22:50:06.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2010-11-22T22:50:06.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 4 by b...@google.com</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=1142#c4" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/1142/comments/full/4" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>